      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Note\n\nThis absence is chemically unsurprising for two reasons:\n1. **Aspirin hydrolyzes rapidly in aqueous solution** to salicylate (2-hydroxybenzoate) and acetic acid, so any real-world Pu(IV)–\"aspirin\" interaction would actually be a Pu(IV)–salicylate interaction.\n2. **Pu(IV) is a hard, highly charged cation** (charge +4) that strongly prefers hard oxygen donors like fluoride, oxalate, and hydroxide — the ligands that *do* appear in SRD-46. Carboxylate complexes of Pu(IV) with aromatic ligands are rarely studied under well-defined aqueous conditions.\n\nIf you are interested in the closest analogue, a search for **Pu(IV)–salicylate** would be the recommended next step.\n\n> **Source:** NIST SRD-46 (NIST Standard Reference Database 46 — NIST Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)",
